 Storke On Trial|date=28 May 1899|publisher=The San Francisco Call |page=1|accessdate=18 July 2017|via=newspapers.com}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12441354/yda_addis_storke_guilty_of_libel/|title=Yda Addis Storke Guilty Of Libel|date=22 June 1899|publisher=The San Francisco Call |page=2|accessdate=18 July 2017|via=newspapers.com}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12441392/well_armed_for_her_purpose/|title=Well Armed for Her Purpose|date=10 July 1899|publisher=Alexandria Gazette |page=2|accessdate=18 July 2017|via=newspapers.com}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12441449/tried_to_kill_an_attorey/|title=Tried To Kill An Attorney|date=10 July 1899|publisher=San Francisco Chronicle |page=1|accessdate=18 July 2017|via=newspapers.com}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12441539/yda_addis_sentenced/|title=Yda Addis Sentenced|date=12 July 1899|publisher=Evening Sentinel|location=Santa Cruz, California|page=3|accessdate=18 July 2017|via=newspapers.com}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12441664/police_protection_asked_by_a_man/|title=Police Protection Asked by a Man Threatened by Yda Addis|date=15 July 1899|publisher=The Los Angeles Times |page=9|accessdate=18 July 2017|via=newspapers.com}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12441740/no_indictment_found_against_yda_addis/|title=No Indictment Found Against Yda Addis Storke-Jackson|date=3 December 1899|publisher=The Los Angeles Times |page=7|accessdate=18 July 2017|via=newspapers.com}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12441789/yda_addis_under_close_surveillance/|title=Yda Addis Under Close Surveillance|date=21 December 1899|publisher=Evening Sentinel|location=Santa Cruz, California|page=3|accessdate=18 July 2017|via=newspapers.com}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12441870/yda_addis_storke_is_free/|title=Yda Addis Storke Is Free|date=12 May 1900|publisher=Evening Sentinel|location=Santa Cruz, California|page=3|accessdate=18 July 2017|via=newspapers.com}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Yda-Addiss-Travel-Guide-Territories/dp/0989369560/ref=sr_1_fkmr0_1?keywords=yoda+h.+addis%27s+travel+guide&qid=1578096289&s=books&sr=1-1-fkmr0/|title=Yda H. Addis's Travel Guide}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Addis, Yda Hillis}}\n[[Category:1857 births]]\n[[Category:1900s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:19th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:American translators]]\n[[Category:American women short story writers]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in California]]\n[[Category:19th-century translators]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Mexico]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yda_Hillis_Addis"}
{"title_page": "Utpala dynasty", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox country\n|conventional_long_name =  Utpala dynasty\n|common_name = Utpala dynasty\n|era       = [[Medieval history|Medieval]]\n|government_type = [[Monarchy]] \n|year_start  =  855 CE\n|year_end    =  1003  CE\n|capital          = [[Awantipora|Avantipur]]\n|common_languages = [[Sanskrit language|Sanskrit]]\n|religion         = [[Hinduism]] <br/> [[Buddhism]]\n|title_leader     = Emperor\n|leader1 = [[Avanti Varman (Utpala dynasty)|Avantivarman]]\n|year_leader1 = 855 \u2013 883 CE\n|leader2 =  Shankaravarman\n|year_leader2= 885 \u2013 902 CE\n|leader3 =  [[Didda]]\n|year_leader3= 980 \u2013 1003 CE\n|p1 = Karko\u1e6da Empire\n|s1 = Lohara dynasty\n|today = [[Afghanistan]]<br>[[India]]<br>[[Pakistan]]\n}}\n\n'''Utpala dynasty''' was a [[Hindu]] [[Brahmin]] kingdom which ruled over the [[Kashmir]] region in the northern part of the [[Indian subcontinent]] from 8th to 10th century CE. Several Brahmin dynasties Mikrakula, [[Karkota Empire|Karkota]], [[Utpala dynasty|Utpala]] and Lohara ruled Kashmir until 12th centuary.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Amin|first=Tahir|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=QUVuAAAAMAAJ&dq=lohara+brahman+dynasty&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=brahmin+|title=Mass Resistance in Kashmir: Origins, Evolution, Options|date=1995|publisher=Institute of Policy Studies|language=en}}</ref> The kingdom underwent a few dynasty changes but all through it remained under the control of [[Brahmin|Brahmans]] till the 14th centuary.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mehta|first=Jaswant Lal|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=iUk5k5AN54sC&pg=PA31&lpg=PA31&dq=brahman+shahi+afghanistan&source=bl&ots=KegrVUk93P&sig=ACfU3U19WJtCPyxkQqWJh674V9Y9wVOL4g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwio1o3W1svoAhUz4zgGHRIRBbc4ChDoATADegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=brahman&f=false|title=Advanced Study in the History of Medieval India|date=1979|publisher=Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd|isbn=978-81-207-0617-0|language=en}}</ref> The kingdom was established by [[Avanti Varman (Utpala dynasty)|Avanti Varman]], ending the rule of [[Karkota dynasty]] in 855 CE.<ref name=\"Reign\">{{cite book|title=Ancient Indian History and Civilization|first=Sailendra Nath|last=Sen|publisher=New Age International|year=1999|page=295|isbn=978-8122-411-98-0}}</ref><ref name=\"Suyya\">{{cite book|title=Kashur The Kashmiri Speaking People: Analytical Perspective|first=Mohini Qasba|last=Raina|publisher=Partridge Publishing Singapore|year=2013|isbn=978-1482-899-47-4|page=9}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Amin|first=Tahir|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=QUVuAAAAMAAJ&dq=lohara+brahman+dynasty&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=brahmin+|title=Mass Resistance in Kashmir: Origins, Evolution, Options|date=1995|publisher=Institute of Policy Studies|language=en}}</ref> The cities of [[Awantipora|Avantipur]] and [[Sopore|Suyapur]] were founded during the reign and many [[Hindu temples]] dedicated to both [[Vishnu]] and [[Shiva]] and [[Buddhist monastery|Buddhist monasteries]] were built, notable of which is the [[Awanti Swami temple|Avantiswara and Avantiswami]] temples.<ref name=\"Culture\">{{cite book|title=Cultural heritage of Jammu and Kashmir|page=88|first=K|last=Warikoo|publisher=Pentagon Press|year=2009|isbn=978-8182-743-76-2}}</ref>\n\n== See Also ==\n[[List of Brahmin dynasties and states|List of Brahmin Dynasties and States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:9th-century establishments in India]]\n[[Category:11th-century disestablishments in India]]\n[[Category:History of Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Dynasties of India]]\n[[Category:Hindu dynasties]]\n[[Category:Empires and kingdoms of India]]\n[[Category:Utpala dynasty| ]]\n\n\n{{Asia-royal-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox country\n|conventional_long_name =  Utpala dynasty\n|common_name = Utpala dynasty\n|era       = [[Medieval history|Medieval]]\n|government_type = [[Monarchy]] \n|year_start  =  855 CE\n|year_end    =  1003  CE\n|capital          = [[Awantipora|Avantipur]]\n|common_languages = [[Sanskrit language|Sanskrit]]\n|religion         = [[Hinduism]] <br/> [[Buddhism]]\n|title_leader     = Emperor\n|leader1 = [[Avanti Varman (Utpala dynasty)|Avantivarman]]\n|year_leader1 = 855 \u2013 883 CE\n|leader2 =  Shankaravarman\n|year_leader2= 885 \u2013 902 CE\n|leader3 =  [[Didda]]\n|year_leader3= 980 \u2013 1003 CE\n|p1 = Karko\u1e6da Empire\n|s1 = Lohara dynasty\n|today = [[Afghanistan]]<br>[[India]]<br>[[Pakistan]]\n}}\n\n'''Utpala dynasty''' was a [[Hindu]] kingdom which ruled over the [[Kashmir]] region in the northern part of the [[Indian subcontinent]] from 8th to 10th century CE. The kingdom was established by [[Avanti Varman (Utpala dynasty)|Avanti Varman]], ending the rule of [[Karkota dynasty]] in 855 CE.<ref name=\"Reign\">{{cite book|title=Ancient Indian History and Civilization|first=Sailendra Nath|last=Sen|publisher=New Age International|year=1999|page=295|isbn=978-8122-411-98-0}}</ref><ref name=\"Suyya\">{{cite book|title=Kashur The Kashmiri Speaking People: Analytical Perspective|first=Mohini Qasba|last=Raina|publisher=Partridge Publishing Singapore|year=2013|isbn=978-1482-899-47-4|page=9}}</ref> The cities of [[Awantipora|Avantipur]] and [[Sopore|Suyapur]] were founded during the reign and many [[Hindu temples]] dedicated to both [[Vishnu]] and [[Shiva]] and [[Buddhist monastery|Buddhist monasteries]] were built, notable of which is the [[Awanti Swami temple|Avantiswara and Avantiswami]] temples.<ref name=\"Culture\">{{cite book|title=Cultural heritage of Jammu and Kashmir|page=88|first=K|last=Warikoo|publisher=Pentagon Press|year=2009|isbn=978-8182-743-76-2}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:9th-century establishments in India]]\n[[Category:11th-century disestablishments in India]]\n[[Category:History of Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Dynasties of India]]\n[[Category:Hindu dynasties]]\n[[Category:Empires and kingdoms of India]]\n[[Category:Utpala dynasty| ]]\n\n\n{{Asia-royal-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Doremon9087", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Utpala_dynasty"}
{"title_page": "French ship Tigre (1793)", "text_new": "{{other ships|French ship Tigre}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=French ship Tigre (1793) - View of Lord Bridport's Action off L'Orient, 1795 RMG PX7059 (cropped).jpg\n|Ship image size=\n|Ship caption=''Tigre'' in 1795\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=France\n|Ship flag=[[Image:Flag of French-Navy-Revolution.svg|border|45px|French Navy Ensign]] [[Image:Civil and Naval Ensign of France.svg|border|45px|French Navy Ensign]]\n|Ship name=''Tigre''\n|Ship namesake=[[Tiger]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=Brest\n|Ship laid down=1790\n|Ship launched=8 May 1793\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship captured=22 June 1795\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship country=Great Britain\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Kingdom of Great Britain|naval}}\n|Ship name=''Tigre''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship acquired=22 June 1795 by capture\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship fate=Broken up in June 1817.\n|Ship status=\n|Ship honours=[[Naval General Service Medal (1847)|Naval General Service Medal]] with clasp \"Egypt\"<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=21077|pages=791\u2013792|date=15 March 1850}}</ref>\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Ship class={{sclass-|T\u00e9m\u00e9raire|ship of the line}}\n|Ship displacement=*2966 [[tonne]]s\n*5260 tonnes fully loaded\n|Ship length={{convert|55.87|m|ft}} (172 [[Pied du roi|pied]])\n|Ship beam={{convert|14.90|m|ftin}}\n|Ship draught={{convert|7.26|m|ft}} (22 [[Pied du roi|pied]])\n|Ship propulsion=Up to {{convert|2485|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} of sails\n|Ship armament=*Lower gundeck: 28 \u00d7 [[36-pounder long gun]]s\n*Upper gundeck: 30 \u00d7 [[18-pounder long gun]]s\n*[[Forecastle|Fc]] and [[Quarter deck|QD]]: 16 \u00d7 [[8-pounder long gun]]s + 4 \u00d7 36-pounder [[carronade]]s\n|Ship armour=Timber\n}}\n|}\n'''''Tigre''''' was a [[74-gun]] [[ship of the line]] of the [[French Navy]]. Later it was captured by the British and, as '''HMS ''Tigre''''', operated as part of the [[Royal Navy]] throughout the [[Napoleonic Wars]].\n\n==French service==\n[[File:View of Lord Bridport's Action off L'Orient, 1795 RMG PX7059.jpg|thumb|View of [[Alexander Hood, 1st Viscount Bridport|Lord Bridport]]'s action aboard {{HMS|Royal George|1788|6}} off L'Orient, when ''Tigre'' was captured]]\nHer first captain was [[Pierre Jean Van Stabel]]. When Van Stabel was promoted, she  became the flagship of his 6-ship squadron. She notably fought in 1793 to rescue the French frigate {{ship|French frigate|S\u00e9millante|1792|2}}, along with the ship of the line {{ship|French ship|Jean Bart|1791|2}}.\n\nUnder [[Jacques Bedout]], she took part in the [[Battle of Groix]] where she was captured by the British. She was recommissioned in the [[Royal Navy]] as HMS ''Tigre''.\n\n==British service==\n\nUnder the Royal Navy she assisted in the [[Siege of Acre (1799)|defence of Acre]] during Bonaparte's siege.\n\nOn 8 January 1801 {{HMS|Penelope|1798|2}} captured the French bombard ''St. Roche'', which was carrying wine, liqueurs, ironware, Delfth cloth, and various other merchandise, from Marseilles to Alexandria. {{HMS|Swiftsure|1787|2}}, ''Tigre'', {{HMS|Minotaur|1793|2}}, {{HMS|Northumberland|1798|2}}, {{HMS|Florentina|1800|2}}, and the schooner {{HMS|Malta|1800 schooner|2}}, were in sight and shared in the proceeds of the capture.<ref name=LG15358>{{London Gazette|issue=15358|page=447|date=25 Apr 1801}}</ref>\n\nBecause ''Tigre'' served in the Navy's Egyptian campaign between 8 March 1801 and 2 September, her officers and crew qualified for the clasp \"Egypt\" to the Naval General Service Medal that the [[Admiralty]] authorised in 1850 for all surviving claimants.{{#tag:ref|A first-class share of the prize money awarded in April 1823 was worth [[\u00a3sd|\u00a3]]34 2[[shilling|s]] 4[[pence|d]]; a fifth-class share, that of a seaman, was worth 3s 11\u00bdd. The amount was small as the total had to be shared between 79 vessels and the entire army contingent.<ref>{{London Gazette|page=633 |issue=17915|date=3 April 1823}}</ref>|group=Note}}\n\nAfter the [[Battle of Trafalgar]] on 21 October 1805, ''Tigre'' continued in the blockade of Cadiz. On 25 November, {{HMS|Thunderer|1783|2}} detained the [[Ragusan Republic|Ragusan]] ship ''Nemesis'', which was sailing from [[Isle de France (Mauritius)|Isle de France]] to [[Leghorn, Italy]], with a cargo of spice, [[indigo dye]], and other goods.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15885|page=129|date=28 January 1806}}</ref> ''Tigre'' shared the prize money with ten other British warships.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=16364|page=617|date=24 April 1810}}</ref>\n\nBetween 30 October and 1 November 1809 Admiral [[Benjamin Hallowell Carew|Benjamin Hallowell's]] squadron was at the Bay of [[Roses, Girona|Rosas]]. On 30 October, in the [[Battle of Maguelone]], <ref>{{Cite book|first=On\u00e9sime-Joachim|last=Troude|authorlink=On\u00e9sime-Joachim Troude|year=1867|publisher=Challamel ain\u00e9|url=http://books.google.com/?id=zfFrDVTkcpsC|title=Batailles navales de la France|language=French|volume=4|page=56\u201458}}</ref> boats from ''Tigre'' joined with boats from [[French brig Ronco (1808)|''Tuscan'']], {{HMS|Cumberland|1807|2}}, {{ship|French frigate|Volontaire|1796|2}}, {{HMS|Apollo|1805|2}}, [[HMS Topaze (1793)|''Topaz'']], {{HMS|Philomel|1806|2}}, and {{HMS|Scout|1804|2}} in a cutting out attack after a squadron off the south of France chased an enemy convoy into the Bay of Rosas. The convoy had lost its escorting ships of the line, {{ship|French ship|Robuste|1806|2}} and {{ship|French ship|Lion|1803|2}}, ran aground near [[Frontignan]] and scuttled by their crew, but were nevertheless heavily protected by an armed storeship of 18 guns, two bombards and a [[xebec]]. Some of the British boats took heavy casualties in the clash, but ''Tuscan'' had only one officer slightly wounded, and one seaman dangerously wounded. By the following morning the British had accounted for all eleven vessels in the bay, burning those they did not bring out. <ref>{{London Gazette|issue=16319|date=29 November 1809|pages=1602\u20131604}}</ref> In January 1813 prize money was awarded to the British vessels that took part in the action for the capture of the ships of war ''Gromlire'' and ''Normande'', and of the transports ''Dragon'' and ''Indien''. A court declared {{HMS|Invincible|1808|2}} a joint captor. Head money was also paid for ''Grondire'' and ''Normande'' and for the destruction of ''Lemproye'' and ''Victoire''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue =16698|date=26 January 1813|page=208}}</ref> In 1847 the Admiralty awarded the Naval General Service Medal with clasp \"1 Nov. Boat Service 1809\" to all surviving claimants from the action.\n\n==Fate==\nShe was eventually broken up in June 1817.\n\n==Notes and citations==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{colledge}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|HMS Tigre (ship, 1793)}}\n* {{in lang|fr}} [http://www.netmarine.net/m/bat/tigre/ancien.htm Les b\u00e2timents ayant port\u00e9 le nom de Tigre]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tigre}}\n[[Category:Ships of the line of the French Navy]]\n[[Category:T\u00e9m\u00e9raire-class ships of the line]]\n[[Category:1793 ships]]\n[[Category:Captured ships]]\n[[Category:Ships of the line of the Royal Navy]]\n", "text_old": "{{other ships|French ship Tigre}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=French ship Tigre (1793) - View of Lord Bridport's Action off L'Orient, 1795 RMG PX7059 (cropped).jpg\n|Ship image size=\n|Ship caption=''Tigre'' in 1795\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide 