t of the [[Royal Navy]] throughout the [[Napoleonic Wars]].\n\n==French service==\n[[File:View of Lord Bridport's Action off L'Orient, 1795 RMG PX7059.jpg|thumb|View of [[Alexander Hood, 1st Viscount Bridport|Lord Bridport]]'s action aboard {{HMS|Royal George|1788|6}} off L'Orient, when ''Tigre'' was captured]]\nHer first captain was [[Pierre Jean Van Stabel]]. When Van Stabel was promoted, she  became the flagship of his 6-ship squadron. She notably fought in 1793 to rescue the French frigate {{ship|French frigate|S\u00e9millante|1792|2}}, along with the ship of the line {{ship|French ship|Jean Bart|1791|2}}.\n\nUnder [[Jacques Bedout]], she took part in the [[Battle of Groix]] where she was captured by the British. She was recommissioned in the [[Royal Navy]] as HMS ''Tigre''.\n\n==British service==\n\nUnder the Royal Navy she assisted in the [[Siege of Acre (1799)|defence of Acre]] during Bonaparte's siege.\n\nOn 8 January 1801 {{HMS|Penelope|1798|2}} captured the French bombard ''St. Roche'', which was carrying wine, liqueurs, ironware, Delfth cloth, and various other merchandise, from Marseilles to Alexandria. {{HMS|Swiftsure|1787|2}}, ''Tigre'', {{HMS|Minotaur|1793|2}}, {{HMS|Northumberland|1798|2}}, {{HMS|Florentina|1800|2}}, and the schooner {{HMS|Malta|1800 schooner|2}}, were in sight and shared in the proceeds of the capture.<ref name=LG15358>{{London Gazette|issue=15358|page=447|date=25 Apr 1801}}</ref>\n\nBecause ''Tigre'' served in the Navy's Egyptian campaign between 8 March 1801 and 2 September, her officers and crew qualified for the clasp \"Egypt\" to the Naval General Service Medal that the [[Admiralty]] authorised in 1850 for all surviving claimants.{{#tag:ref|A first-class share of the prize money awarded in April 1823 was worth [[\u00a3sd|\u00a3]]34 2[[shilling|s]] 4[[pence|d]]; a fifth-class share, that of a seaman, was worth 3s 11\u00bdd. The amount was small as the total had to be shared between 79 vessels and the entire army contingent.<ref>{{London Gazette|page=633 |issue=17915|date=3 April 1823}}</ref>|group=Note}}\n\nAfter the [[Battle of Trafalgar]] on 21 October 1805, ''Tigre'' continued in the blockade of Cadiz. On 25 November, {{HMS|Thunderer|1783|2}} detained the [[Ragusan Republic|Ragusan]] ship ''Nemesis'', which was sailing from [[Isle de France (Mauritius)|Isle de France]] to [[Leghorn, Italy]], with a cargo of spice, [[indigo dye]], and other goods.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15885|page=129|date=28 January 1806}}</ref> ''Tigre'' shared the prize money with ten other British warships.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=16364|page=617|date=24 April 1810}}</ref>\n\nBetween 30 October and 1 November 1809 Admiral [[Benjamin Hallowell Carew|Benjamin Hallowell's]] squadron was at the Bay of [[Roses, Girona|Rosas]]. On 30 October, in the [[Battle of Maguelone]]. <ref>{{Cite book|first=On\u00e9sime-Joachim|last=Troude|authorlink=On\u00e9sime-Joachim Troude|year=1867|publisher=Challamel ain\u00e9|url=http://books.google.com/?id=zfFrDVTkcpsC|title=Batailles navales de la France|language=French|volume=4|page=56\u201458}}</ref> boats from ''Tigre'' joined with boats from [[French brig Ronco (1808)|''Tuscan'']], {{HMS|Cumberland|1807|2}}, {{ship|French frigate|Volontaire|1796|2}}, {{HMS|Apollo|1805|2}}, [[HMS Topaze (1793)|''Topaz'']], {{HMS|Philomel|1806|2}}, and {{HMS|Scout|1804|2}} in a cutting out attack after a squadron off the south of France chased an enemy convoy into the Bay of Rosas. The convoy had lost its escorting ships of the line, {{ship|French ship|Robuste|1806|2}} and {{ship|French ship|Lion|1803|2}}, ran aground near [[Frontignan]] and scuttled by their crew, but were nevertheless heavily protected by an armed storeship of 18 guns, two bombards and a [[xebec]]. Some of the British boats took heavy casualties in the clash, but ''Tuscan'' had only one officer slightly wounded, and one seaman dangerously wounded. By the following morning the British had accounted for all eleven vessels in the bay, burning those they did not bring out. <ref>{{London Gazette|issue=16319|date=29 November 1809|pages=1602\u20131604}}</ref> In January 1813 prize money was awarded to the British vessels that took part in the action for the capture of the ships of war ''Gromlire'' and ''Normande'', and of the transports ''Dragon'' and ''Indien''. A court declared {{HMS|Invincible|1808|2}} a joint captor. Head money was also paid for ''Grondire'' and ''Normande'' and for the destruction of ''Lemproye'' and ''Victoire''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue =16698|date=26 January 1813|page=208}}</ref> In 1847 the Admiralty awarded the Naval General Service Medal with clasp \"1 Nov. Boat Service 1809\" to all surviving claimants from the action.\n\n==Fate==\nShe was eventually broken up in June 1817.\n\n==Notes and citations==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{colledge}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|HMS Tigre (ship, 1793)}}\n* {{in lang|fr}} [http://www.netmarine.net/m/bat/tigre/ancien.htm Les b\u00e2timents ayant port\u00e9 le nom de Tigre]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tigre}}\n[[Category:Ships of the line of the French Navy]]\n[[Category:T\u00e9m\u00e9raire-class ships of the line]]\n[[Category:1793 ships]]\n[[Category:Captured ships]]\n[[Category:Ships of the line of the Royal Navy]]\n", "name_user": "Rama", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBritish service", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_ship_Tigre_(1793)"}
{"title_page": "Roberta Collins", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| image         = \n| name          = Roberta Collins\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1944|11|17}}\n| birth_place   = [[Alhambra, California]], U.S.\n| birthname     = Roberta Lee Hefley\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|2008|8|16|1944|11|17}}\n| death_place   = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| death_cause   = Overdose of drugs and alcohol\n| yearsactive   = 1969\u20131986\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Gunther Collins|1966|1970|end=divorced}}\n| children      = 1\n| occupation    = Actress\n}}\n\n'''Roberta Collins''' (November 17, 1944 \u2013 August 16, 2008)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.ancestrylibrary.com/cgi-bin/sse.dll?_phsrc=CUG19&_phstart=successSource&usePUBJs=true&gss=angs-c&new=1&rank=1&msT=1&gsfn=Roberta%20&gsfn_x=0&gsln=Collins&gsln_x=0&msbdy=1944&msbpn__ftp=Los%20Angeles%20County,%20California,%20USA&msbpn=1813&msbpn_PInfo=7-%7C0%7C1652393%7C0%7C2%7C0%7C7%7C0%7C1813%7C0%7C0%7C0%7C&MSAV=1&uidh=57k&pcat=34&h=83168138&recoff=11%2012&dbid=3693&indiv=1&ml_rpos=1|title=Ancestry Library Edition|website=Search.ancestrylibrary.com|accessdate=2016-12-29}}</ref> was a film and television actress who was known for her attractive physique, blonde, curly hair, and [[Marilyn Monroe]] appearance. She starred in many exploitation films, including the prostitute Clara in [[Tobe Hooper]]'s ''[[Eaten Alive]]'', and as Matilda the Hun in the science-fiction film ''[[Death Race 2000]]''.\n\n[[Jack Hill]], who directed her in ''[[The Big Doll House]]'', said of her, \"I think she could have had a great career, but she couldn't get her personal life together ... she would be fantastic one day, do everything right, and then she would be out until 4 am partying and the next day she would be useless.\"<ref>Callum Waddell, ''Jack Hill'', MacFarland (2009), pg. 151<!--ISSN/ISBN needed--></ref>\n\n==Career==\nCollins was born Roberta Lee Hefley in 1944. She was married to Gunther Collins from 1966\u201370 and took his surname. The couple had one child, a son, Michael. She won numerous beauty contests growing up and signed to a contract with a studio almost immediately after graduation from high school. However, her option was not picked up, something that was repeated with another studio, \"so that made me want to study and become a good actress\", she later said.<ref>Lane, Lydia. \"BEAUTY: Olive Oil for Natural Facial\", ''Los Angeles Times'' (1923-Current File), [Los Angeles, Calif], June 28, 1976, p. f4.</ref>\n\nIn 1969, she was appointed queen of the Warner Bros-Seven Arts International Film Festival in Freeport, Grand Bahamas Island.<ref>Roberta Collins Queen of Festival Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) [Los Angeles, Calif], May 8, 1969, p. f17.</ref> She gained a level of fame with her appearance in the enormously popular ''The Big Doll House''. This led to a series of roles in exploitation films. She worked in a number of nonexploitation roles, as well, notably on television.\n\nIn the early 1970s, Collins briefly dated [[Glenn Ford]].<ref>Henry Berger, Chef, Take Turns Noting Year of Rat Jacobs, Jody. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) [Los Angeles, Calif], February 23, 1972.</ref> In the early 1990s, she reportedly worked as a caregiver for Ford.<ref>Peter Ford, ''Glenn Ford: A Life'', pg. 300</ref>\n\n==Death==\nCollins died August 16, 2008, from a reportedly accidental overdose of a cocktail of drugs and alcohol.{{Where|date=December 2016}}<ref>Lentz, Harris, I, II (2008, 12). [http://search.proquest.com/docview/2143543 Obituaries: Roberta Collins], 64 - August 16, 2008.</ref> Her son predeceased her.<ref>http://www.elijahdrenner.com/2015/01/roommates-wanted/</ref> She is buried at the [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]].\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2014,  a tribute to Collins was part of the [[St. Louis International Film Festival]]. ''[[Caged Heat]]'' was screened and in a concert, [[Stace England]] and the Screen Syndicate played an album of songs inspired by Roberta Collins.<ref>{{cite web|author=Tom Stockman |url=http://www.wearemoviegeeks.com/2014/11/sliff-interview-stace-england/ |title=SLIFF Interview: Stace England of Screen Syndicate - A Tribute to Roberta Collins |publisher=We Are Movie Geeks |date=2014-11-19 |accessdate=2016-12-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Tom Stockman |url=http://www.wearemoviegeeks.com/2014/10/sliff-2014-roberta-collins-tribute-screening-caged-heat-live-music-november-22nd/ |title=SLIFF 2014 - Roberta Collins Tribute with Screening of CAGED HEAT & Live Music November 22nd |publisher=We Are Movie Geeks |date=2014-10-26 |accessdate=2016-12-29}}</ref>\n\n==Partial filmography==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*''[[Lord Love a Duck]]'' (1966) - Brunette high school classmate (uncredited)\n*''[[Adam-12]]'' (1969, TV Series, episode \"Log 153: Find Me a Needle\") - Sally\n*''[[Here Come the Brides]]'' (1970, TV Series, episode \"Pat's Girl\") - Pat's girl\n*''[[The Bob Hope Show]]'' (1970)\n*''[[The Big Doll House]]'' (1971) - Alcott\n*''[[Women in Cages]]'' (1971) - Stoke\n*''[[Cade's County]]'' (1971, TV Series, episode \"Requiem for Miss Madrid\") - Karen Malloy\n*''[[Minnie and Moskowitz]]'' (1971) - Countergirl at Pink's Hot Dogs (uncredited)\n*''[[Sweet Kill]]'' (1972) - Call girl\n*''[[Unholy Rollers]]'' (1972) - Jennifer\n*''[[The Roommates]]'' (1973) - Beth\n* ''[[Wonder Women (film)|Wonder Women]]'' (1973) - Laura\n*''[[The Last Porno Flick]]'' (1974)\n*''[[Caged Heat]]'' (1974) - Belle Tyson\n*''[[Three the Hard Way (film)|Three the Hard Way]]'' (1974) - Lait's secretary\n*''[[Movin' On (TV series)|Movin' On]]'' (1974, TV Series, episode \"The Time of His Life\") - Lucille\n*''[[Kolchak: The Night Stalker]]'' (1974, TV Series, episode \"The Ripper\") - Det. Cortazzo\n*''[[The Rockford Files]]'' (1974, TV Series, episode \"Exit Prentiss Carr\") - Nancy Hellman\n*''Alias Big Cherry'' (1975)\n*''[[Death Race 2000]]'' (1975) - Matilda the Hun\n*''Train Ride to Hollywood'' (1975) - Jean Harlow\n*''[[The Witch Who Came From the Sea]]'' (1976) - Clarissa\n*''[[Eaten Alive]]'' (1976) - Clara\n*''Whiskey Mountain'' (1977) - Diana\n*''[[Speedtrap]]'' (1977) - Ms. Hastings, student driver\n*''[[79 Park Avenue]]'' (1977, TV Mini-Series) - Lola\n*''[[Matilda (1978 film)|Matilda]]'' (1978) - Tanya Six\n*''[[B.J. and the Bear]]'' (1979, episode \"Shine On\") - Ellen Smith\n*''[[Saturday the 14th]]'' (1981) - Cousin Rhonda\n*''[[Death Wish II]]'' (1982) - Woman at party\n*''[[Hardbodies]]'' (1984) - Lana\n*''[[School Spirit]]'' (1985) - Helen Grimshaw\n*''[[Hardbodies 2]]'' (1986) - Lana Logan\n*''[[Vendetta (1986 film)|Vendetta]]'' (1986) - Miss Dice (final film role)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==Notes==\n*{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/Femme_Fatales_v07n05/page/n41|magazine=Femme Fetales|first=Frederick|last=Szebin|title=Roberta Collins|page=41\u201347|volume=7|number=5}}\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0172646}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Collins, Roberta}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Drug-related deaths in California]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| image         = \n| name          = Roberta Collins\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1944|11|17}}\n| birth_place   = [[Alhambra, California]], U.S.\n| birthname     = Roberta Lee Hefley\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|2008|8|16|1944|11|17}}\n| death_place   = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| death_cause   = Overdose of drugs and alcohol\n| yearsactive   = 1969\u20131986\n| spouse        = Gunther Collins (1966-70; divorced); 1 child\n| occupation    = Actress\n}}\n\n'''Roberta Collins''' (November 17, 1944 \u2013 August 16, 2008)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.ancestrylibrary.com/cgi-bin/sse.dll?_phsrc=CUG19&_phstart=successSource&usePUBJs=true&gss=angs-c&new=1&rank=1&msT=1&gsfn=Roberta%20&gsfn_x=0&gsln=Collins&gsln_x=0&msbdy=1944&msbpn__ftp=Los%20Angeles%20County,%20California,%20USA&msbpn=1813&msbpn_PInfo=7-%7C0%7C1652393%7C0%7C2%7C0%7C7%7C0%7C1813%7C0%7C0%7C0%7C&MSAV=1&uidh=57k&pcat=34&h=83168138&recoff=11%2012&dbid=3693&indiv=1&ml_rpos=1|title=Ancestry Library Edition|website=Search.ancestrylibrary.com|accessdate=2016-12-29}}</ref> was a film and television actress who was known for her attractive physique, blonde, curly hair, and [[Marilyn Monroe]] appearance. She starred in many exploitation films, including the prostitute Clara in [[Tobe Hooper]]'s ''[[Eaten Alive]]'', and as Matilda the Hun in the science-fiction film ''[[Death Race 2000]]''.\n\n[[Jack Hill]], who directed her in ''[[The Big Doll House]]'', said of her, \"I think she could have had a great career, but she couldn't get her personal life together ... she would be fantastic one day, do everything right, and then she would be out until 4 am partying and the next day she would be useless.\"<ref>Callum Waddell, ''Jack Hill'', MacFarland (2009), pg. 151<!--ISSN/ISBN needed--></ref>\n\n==Career==\nCollins was born Roberta Lee Hefley in 1944. She was married to Gunther Collins from 1966\u201370 and took his surname. The couple had one child, a son, Michael. She won numerous beauty contests growing up and signed to a contract with a studio almost immediately after graduation from high school. However, her option was not picked up, something that was repeated with another studio, \"so that made me want to study and become a good actress\", she later said.<ref>Lane, Lydia. \"BEAUTY: Olive Oil for Natural Facial\", ''Los Angeles Times'' (1923-Current File), [Los Angeles, Calif], June 28, 1976, p. f4.</ref>\n\nIn 1969, she was appointed queen of the Warner Bros-Seven Arts International Film Festival in Freeport, Grand Bahamas Island.<ref>Roberta Collins Queen of Festival Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) [Los Angeles, Calif], May 8, 1969, p. f17.</ref> She gained a level of fame with her appearance in the enormously popular ''The Big Doll House''. This led to a series of roles in exploitation films. She worked in a number of nonexploitation roles, as well, notably on television.\n\nIn the early 1970s, Collins briefly dated [[Glenn Ford]].<ref>Henry Berger, Chef, Take Turns Noting Year of Rat Jacobs, Jody. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) [Los Angeles, Calif], February 23, 1972.</ref> In the early 1990s, she reportedly worked as a caregiver for Ford.<ref>Peter Ford, ''Glenn Ford: A Life'', pg. 300</ref>\n\n==Death==\nCollins died August 16, 2008, from a reportedly accidental overdose of a cocktail of drugs and alcohol.{{Where|date=December 2016}}<ref>Lentz, Harris, I, II (2008, 12). [http://search.proquest.com/docview/2143543 Obituaries: Roberta Collins], 64 - August 16, 2008.</ref> Her son predeceased her.<ref>http://www.elijahdrenner.com/2015/01/roommates-wanted/</ref> She is buried at the [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]].\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2014,  a tribute to Collins was part of the [[St. Louis International Film Festival]]. ''[[Caged Heat]]'' was screened and in a concert, [[Stace England]] and the Screen Syndicate played an album of songs inspired by Roberta Collins.<ref>{{cite web|author=Tom Stockman |url=http://www.wearemoviegeeks.com/2014/11/sliff-interview-stace-england/ |title=SLIFF Interview: Stace England of Screen Syndicate - A Tribute to Roberta Collins |publisher=We Are Movie Geeks |date=2014-11-19 |accessdate=2016-12-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Tom Stockman |url=http://www.wearemoviegeeks.com/2014/10/sliff-2014-roberta-collins-tribute-screening-caged-heat-live-music-november-22nd/ |title=SLIFF 2014 - Roberta Collins Tribute with Screening of CAGED HEAT & Live Music November 22nd |publisher=We Are Movie Geeks |date=2014-10-26 |accessdate=2016-12-29}}</ref>\n\n==Partial filmography==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*''[[