}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==Notes==\n*{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/Femme_Fatales_v07n05/page/n41|magazine=Femme Fetales|first=Frederick|last=Szebin|title=Roberta Collins|page=41\u201347|volume=7|number=5}}\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0172646}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Collins, Roberta}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Drug-related deaths in California]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]]\n", "name_user": "Jmg38", "label": "safe", "comment": "box tools", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roberta_Collins"}
{"title_page": "Marc Gafni", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name          = Marc Gafni\n|image         = MarcGafni.jpg\n|image_size    = \n|caption       = Marc Gafni in Rome\n|birth_name    = Marc Winiarz\n|birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1960}}\n|birth_place   = [[Pittsfield, Massachusetts]]\n|nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n|other_names   = Mordechai Gafni, Mark Gafni, Mordechai Winiarz, Mordechai Winyarz\n|education     = [[Queens College]], [[Oxford University]]\n}}\n'''Marc Gafni''' (born Marc Winiarz) is an American author and former rabbi who became a New Age spiritual teacher.<ref name=\"Rosenblatt04\"><!-- Archived article has new title of \"A Rabbi Accused of Sexual Abuse Seeks to Reinvent Himself\" but is the same as the original \"The Re-Invented Rabbi\" -->{{cite web|url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/top/editcolcontent.php3|title=The Re-Invented Rabbi|last=Rosenblatt|first=Gary|authorlink=Gary Rosenblatt|date=September 24, 2004|work=Between the Lines|publisher=[[The Jewish Week]]|archiveurl=http://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/a-rabbi-accused-of-sexual-abuse-seeks-to-reinvent-himself/|archivedate=September 30, 2004|accessdate=January 11, 2008}}</ref> One of his rabbinical ordinations was voluntarily returned and another revoked for sexual misconduct.<ref name=\"catalyst\">{{cite journal\n | last = Bell\n | first = Jeff\n |author2=Greta Belanger deJong\n |date=July 2008\n | title = Trial by Internet: An archetypal spiritual drama\n | journal = Catalyst Magazine\n | volume = 27\n | issue = 7\n | pages = 20\u201325\n | publisher = Catalyst Magazine\n | location = [[Salt Lake City]], [[Utah]]\n | url = http://www.catalystmagazine.net/pdfs/0708/catalyst_0708.pdf\n | archiveurl = http://www.catalystmagazine.net/trial-by-internet-an-archetypal-spiritual-drama/\n | archivedate = October 5, 2011\n | accessdate = December 29, 2016\n}}\n</ref><ref name = \"POJ-RR\" /><ref name = \"TantricGuru\">{{cite magazine\n| last       = Kestenbaum\n| first      = Sam\n| date       = August 2, 2016\n| title      = Former Rabbi, Accused Molester Marc Gafni Teaching at Tantric Sex School\n| url        = http://forward.com/news/346632/controverisal-new-age-guru-marc-gafnis-latest-venture-teacher-in-residence/\n| magazine   = [[The Forward]]\n| location   = New York\n| access-date= April 20, 2017\n}}\n</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewschool.com/2006/05/10681/reb-zalman-speaks-on-gafni/|title=Reb Zalman Speaks on Gafni \u00b7 Jewschool|date=2006-05-26|website=Jewschool|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> Accused of sexual assault by multiple women, Gafni acknowledged a nine-month \"relationship\" with a 14-year-old girl when he was 19;<ref name=\"Rosenblatt04\" /><ref name = \"Oppenheimer2015\">{{cite news\n| last         = Oppenheimer\n| first        = Marc\n| date         = December 25, 2015\n| title        = A Spiritual Leader Gains Stature, Trailed by a Troubled Past\n| url          = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/26/us/marc-gafni-center-for-integral-wisdom.html?smid=tw-share\n| newspaper    = [[The New York Times]]\n| access-date  = December 29, 2015\n}}\n</ref><ref name = Friedman2015>{{cite news\n| last         = Friedman\n| first        = Gabe\n| date         = December 29, 2015\n| title        = 4 quotes by ex-Orthodox rabbi Marc Gafni not in The NY Times article\n| url          = http://www.jta.org/2015/12/29/news-opinion/the-telegraph/4-quotes-by-ex-orthodox-rabbi-marc-gafni-that-the-ny-times-didnt-include\n| newspaper    = [[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]\n| access-date  = January 3, 2016\n}}\n</ref> he denies the \"relationship\" was abusive, describing it as consensual.<ref name = forward2>{{cite magazine\n| last       = Gafni\n| first      = Marc\n| date       = November 3, 2016\n| title      = Marc Gafni Tells His Story \u2014 and Experts Respond\n| url        = http://forward.com/opinion/353202/marc-gafni-tells-his-story-and-experts-respond/\n| magazine   = [[The Forward]]\n| location   = New York\n| access-date= December 15, 2016\n}}\n</ref><ref name = \"DN_McShane\">{{cite news\n| last1                 = McShane\n| first1                = Larry\n| date                  = January 2, 2016\n| title                 = New Age guru Marc Gafni allegedly molested two NYC teen girls during the 1980s, denies sexual misconduct allegations\n| url                   = http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/marc-gafni-denies-sexual-misconduct-allegations-article-1.2483567\n| newspaper             = [[New York Daily News]]\n| access-date           = December 29, 2016\n}}\n</ref><ref name = \"jewishforward\">{{cite news\n| last1                 = Ledger\n| first1                = Online\n| date                  = November 9, 2016\n| title                 = Marc Gafni: I never molested 13-year-old girl\n\n| url                   = http://www.jewishledger.com/2016/11/marc-gafni-never-molested-13-year-old-girl/\n| newspaper             = Jewish Ledger\n| access-date           = March 26, 2017\n}}\n</ref> The alleged victim states that she was 13. In 2019, Gafni was named in a sexual abuse lawsuit against Yeshiva University.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://forward.com/fast-forward/430202/marc-gafni-sexual-abuse-lawsuit-yeshiva-university/|title=Marc Gafni Named In Latest Sexual Abuse Lawsuit Against Yeshiva University|last=Feldman|first=Ari|date=|work=Forward|access-date=2019-12-28|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iapps.courts.state.ny.us/nyscef/ViewDocument?docIndex=8NgEt9dgNg9jl8rRf1DM1g==|title=Jane Doe v Yeshiva University and Marc Gafni, previously known as Mordechai Winiarz; Plaintiff Affadavit|last=|first=|date=2019-08-14|website=Supreme Court of the State of New York|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nGafni was born in 1960<ref name = \"Oppenheimer2015\" /> to [[Holocaust survivors]] in [[Pittsfield, Massachusetts]].<ref name = \"POJ-RR\">{{citation |url= http://www.haaretz.com/post-orthodoxy-journey-1.115864 |title= Post-Orthodoxy Journey |last= Livneh |first= Neri |date= March 4, 2004 |newspaper= [[Haaretz]]}}</ref> Gafni was educated at Modern-Orthodox [[yeshiva]]s in the [[New York City]] area. In the 1980s, while attending [[Yeshiva University]],<ref name = \"POJ-RR\" /> Gafni worked with Jewish Public School Youth, an organization providing Jewish social clubs in public schools.<ref name=\"NYP\">{{cite news\n|url= http://www.nypost.com/news/regionalnews/66361.htm\n|title= Fiend Rabbi On Run\n|accessdate= December 28, 2016\n|last= Montefinise\n|first= Angela\n|date= May 21, 2006\n|newspaper= [[New York Post]]\n|pages = 25\n|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060614154413/http://www.nypost.com/news/regionalnews/66361.htm\n|archivedate= 2006-06-14\n}}\n</ref> In 1988, Gafni also worked as a rabbi in [[Boca Raton]], [[Florida]].<ref name=\"Rosenblatt04\" /> After making [[aliyah]], Gafni served as rabbi of the [[West Bank]] settlement of [[Tzofim]].<ref name = \"Ynet-Raved\">{{cite news\n| last1                 = Raved\n| first1                = Ahiya\n| last2                 = Cohen\n| first2                = Avi\n| date                  = May 18, 2006\n| title                 = Rabbi Gafni accused of sexual assault\n| url                   = http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3252577,00.html\n| department            = News\n| website               = [[Ynetnews]]\n| access-date           = December 28, 2016\n}}\n</ref> When Gafni moved to Israel he hebraicized his name. \"Winiarz,\" Polish for \"vintner,\" is related to the [[Hebrew]] word {{transl|he|ISO|''gefen''}} ({{rtl-lang|he|\u05d2\u05e4\u05df}}), which means \"grape\"\u2014thus the name \"Gafni.\" Gafni has three children from previous marriages<ref name = \"POJ-RR\" /> and one child with Mariana Caplan.<ref name = \"Caplan\">{{cite web\n| title       = About the Founders\n| url         = http://centerforintegralwisdom.org/ciw-founders/\n| publisher   = Center for Integral Wisdom\n| year        = 2015\n| accessdate  = December 29, 2015\n}}\n</ref><ref name = \"CIWS Bio\">{{cite web\n |url        = http://www.ievolve.org/leadership/executive-officers/#Marc_Gafni_DPhil\n |title      = Marc Gafni, D.Phil.\n |year       = 2013\n |work       = Executive Officers\n |publisher  = Center for World Spirituality\n |accessdate = February 27, 2013\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Education===\nGafni majored in philosophy as an undergraduate at Queens College, and earned his doctorate in philosophy from [[Oxford University]].<ref name = \"POJ-RR\" /><ref name = psychologytoday>{{cite magazine\n | url = https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/ethical-wisdom/201509/evolutionary-love-interview-dr-marc-gafni\n | title = Evolutionary Love: An Interview With Dr. Marc Gafni\n | last = Matousek\n | first = Mark\n | date = September 8, 2015\n | magazine = Psychology Today\n | access-date = December 29, 2016\n}}\n</ref> He returned one rabbinical ordination ''[[semikhah|(semikhah]])'' to \"spare his former teacher\" (Rabbi [[Shlomo Riskin ]]) \"any further embarrassment\".<ref name=\"Rosenblatt04\"/> His other rabbinical ordination by [[Zalman Schachter-Shalomi|Reb Zalman Schachter-Shalomi]] was revoked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewschool.com/2006/05/10681/reb-zalman-speaks-on-gafni/|title=Reb Zalman Speaks on Gafni \u00b7 Jewschool|date=2006-05-26|website=Jewschool|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/us-jewish-group-spurns-ex-rabbi-over-his-sexual-behavior/|title=US Jewish group spurns ex-rabbi over his sexual behavior|last=JTA|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n\n== Teachings ==\nGafni's teachings are described as [[Integral theory (Ken Wilber)|integral]] or world [[spirituality]], incorporating traditional religious studies with contemporary themes, and are aimed at spirituality for people who do not identify with one specific religion.<ref name = \"POJ-RR\"/><ref name=haaretz>{{cite news|last=Ganihar|first=Tomer|title=Death of the spirit|url=http://www.haaretz.com/weekend/week-s-end/death-of-the-spirit-1.366510|newspaper=Haaretz|date=June 7, 2011}}</ref> Gafni describes himself and his students as \"dual citizens\" of both their native traditional religion and the broader themes of \"world spirituality\".<ref name = \"POJ-RR\"/><ref name=dual>{{cite web|title=A Passport for Dual Citizenship with Michael Murphy & Marc Gafni|url=http://www.ievolve.org/tag/dual-citizenship/|publisher=Center for World Spirituality|date=August 8, 2011|access-date=March 3, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602103525/http://www.ievolve.org/tag/dual-citizenship/|archive-date=June 2, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> He advocates a new set of teachings around [[Eros (concept)|eros]], [[Human sexuality|sexuality]] and [[Intimate relationship|relationships]] in his book ''Mystery of Love'' and CD set ''Erotic and the Holy''.<ref name=jweek>{{cite news|last=Wall|first=Alexandra|title=Let love, sex and holiness make your life full, says rabbi|url=http://www.jweekly.com/article/full/19850/let-love-sex-and-holiness-make-your-life-full-says-rabbi/|newspaper=J Weekly|date=May 9, 2003}}</ref><ref name = \"Rosnblum2006\">{{cite news\n| url         = http://www.jpost.com/Opinion/Columnists/Think-Again-Sexualizing-the-public-square\n| title       = Think Again: 'Sexualizing' the public square \n| accessdate  = December 28, 2016\n| last        = Rosenblum\n| first       = Jonathan\n| authorlink  = Jonathan Rosenblum\n| date        = July 13, 2006\n| newspaper   = [[The Jerusalem Post]]\n}} See also Gafni, ''The Erotic And The Holy: Kabbalistic Tantra for Everyday Living''</ref> At the core of his message is what Gafni refers to as the unique self.<ref name  = \"GafniAbsract\">{{cite web\n | url = http://uniqueself.com/unique-self-theory/unique-self-basics/marc-gafni-on-unique-self/the-evolutionary-emergent-of-unique-self/\n | title = The Evolutionary Emergent of Unique Self (Abstract)\n | last = Gafni\n | first = Marc\n | year = 2011\n | website = Unique Self\n | access-date = December 20, 2016\n}}\n</ref> Gafni believes that \"the sexual is the ultimate Spiritual Master\" and has written \"I was convinced from an early age that religion had lost what I believed must have been its original erotic vitality\u2026I knew that the sexual, if liberated and ethically expressed, must somehow hold the mystery of return to the much larger-than-sexual Eros.\"<ref name = \"TantricGuru\" />\n\nIn 2010, Gafni, Mariana Caplan\u2014the mother of his son,<ref name = \"Caplan\"/> Sally Kempton, and Lori Galperin, founded the Center for World Spirituality.<ref name = \"CSWFounding\">{{cite web\n | url = http://centerforintegralwisdom.org/ciw-founders/\n | title = Founders\n | author = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->\n | year = 2015\n | website = Center for Integral Wisdom\n | access-date = December 19, 2016\n}}\n</ref> At the Center, Gafni and [[Ken Wilber]] founded a Wisdom Council to envision a spirituality based on Integral Principles.<ref name = \"CaplanCommonGround\">{{cite magazine\n| last       = Caplan\n| first      = Mariana\n| year       = 2011\n| issue      = December 2010/January 2011\n| title      = Los Angeles Makes Movies. San Francisco Makes Movements.\n| url        = http://onlinedigitaleditions2.com/commonground/archive/web-12-2010/\n| magazine   = Common Ground Magazine\n| pages      = 64\u201365\n| location   = [[Mill Valley, California]]\n| publisher  = Rob Sidon\n| access-date= December 19, 2016\n}}\n</ref> The Wisdom Council includes members such as Gafni, Wilber, [[Tony Robbins]], [[Warren Farrell]], Lori Galperin, Sally Kempton.<ref name=wisdomcouncil>{{cite web|title=Wisdom Council|url=http://www.ievolve.org/leadership/world-spirituality-council/|publisher=iEvolve|access-date=2013-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307165015/http://www.ievolve.org/leadership/world-spirituality-council/|archive-date=2013-03-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> The co-chair of Center for World Spirituality was [[Whole Foods]] [[CEO]] [[John Mackey (businessman)|John Mackey]].<ref name=mac>{{cite web|title=What is a purpose-driven business?: John Mackey and Marc Gafni in Dialogue, Part 2|url=http://www.ievolve.org/world-spirituality-unplugged-what-is-a-purpose-driven-business-john-mackey-and-marc-gafni-in-dialogue-part-1%E2%80%B3/|publisher=iEvolve|date=October 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\nGafni was a Scholar in Residence at the Integral Institute and the Director of the Integral Spiritual Experience but was asked to leave after the 2011 allegations of his sexual misconduct.<ref name = \"JW 09132011\">{{cite news\n |url          = http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/brief/new_sexual_complaints_against_marc_gafni\n |title        = New Sexual Complaints Against Marc Gafni\n |last1        = Rosenblatt\n |first1       = Gary\n |authorlink1  = Gary Rosenblatt\n |date         = September 13, 2011\n |newspaper    = [[The Jewish Week]]\n |accessdate   = December 28, 2016\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Writing===\nGafni is the author of eight books on spirituality and religion, including the 2001 ''Soul Prints''.<ref name=\"catalyst\"/> Marc Gafni's second English-language book, ''The Mystery of Love'', was later converted to an audio lecture series called ''The Erotic and the Holy'', published by [[Sounds True]]. He also co-authored ''Who is Afraid of Lilith? Rereading the Kabbalah of the Feminine Shadow'' with Ohad Ezrachi.<ref name = \"FreeLibraryLilith\">{{cite web\n | url = https://www.thefreelibrary.com/When+the+Rabbi+Met+Lilith.-a0133901938\n | title = When the Rabbi Met Lilith.\n | author = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->\n | date = July 11, 2005\n | website =  The Free Library\n | publisher = [[PR Newswire]]\n | access-date = December 21, 2016\n}}\n</ref> He wrote ''Radical Kabbalah'', a two-volume work published by Integral Publishers in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Integral Publishers|url=http://integralpublishers.com/ip_books/}}</ref> In 2012, he published ''Your Unique Self: The Radical Path to Personal Enlightenment'' with a foreword written by Wilber.<ref name = \"YUS_Forward\">{{cite web| url = http://uniqueself.com/about-the-book/take-a-look/| title = Take a Look at the Table of Contents| year = 2016| website = Unique Self| publisher = Center for Integral Wisdom| access-date = January 4, 2016}}</ref> It won a 2012 USA Best Book Awards in Spirituality: General category.<ref name = \"USABook2012\">{{cite web\n | url = http://www.usabooknews.com/images/2012_results.pdf\n | title = 2012 Reseults\n | author = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> \n | website = [[USA Book News]]\n | access-date = December 19, 2016\n | format = PDF \n | quote = }}\n</ref>\n\n===Television===\nWhile in Israel, Gafni hosted {{transl|he|ISO|''Tahat Gafno''}} ({{lang-he|\u05ea\u05d7\u05ea \u05d2\u05e4\u05e0\u05d5|lit=under his vine}}), a television program broadcast on Israel's [[Channel 2 (Israel)|Channel 2]].<ref name = \"POJ-RR\"/> Gafni also did a series of weekly television spots with Israeli comedian Gil Kopatch on biblical wisdom for every day life.<ref name = \"Kopatch2005\">{{cite news\n| last         = Kopatch\n| first        = Gil\n| date         = June 2, 2005\n| title        = Why Am I Not a Buddhist? \n| url          = http://www.haaretz.com/why-am-i-not-a-buddhist-1.160186\n| newspaper    = [[Haaretz]]\n| access-date  = December 28, 2016\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Sexual assault allegations==\nGafni has been accused of sexual assault multiple times dating back to the 1980s.<ref name=\"Rosenblatt04\"/><ref name = \"Oppenheimer2015\" /><ref name=\"NYP\" /><ref name = \"JW 09132011\" />\n\nIn early January 2016, Judy Mitzner alleged that she was one of two teenage girls whom Gafni molested in New York City in 1986.<ref name = \"Prince\">{{cite news |last=Prince |first=Cathryn J. |date=January 6, 2016 |title=Controversial ex-rabbi Gafni and an alleged victim square off |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/controversial-ex-rabbi-gafni-and-an-alleged-victim-square-off/ |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |access-date=February 7, 2018}}</ref> She reiterated those claims on an appearance on the [[Dr. Phil (talk show)|Dr. Phil]] show of January 19, 2018, in which Gafni also appeared.<ref name = \"Pink\">{{cite magazine|last=Pink|first=Aiden|date=January 21, 2018|title=Accused Child Molester Marc Gafni Defends Himself On 'Dr. Phil'|url=https://forward.com/fast-forward/392482/accused-child-molester-marc-gafni-defends-himself-on-dr-phil/|magazine=[[The Forward]]|location=[[New York City]]|access-date=February 7, 2018}}</ref> Mitzner was 16 and Gafni was 24 and he was her Jewish Youth Leader at the time.<ref>{{Citation|title=Alleged Victim Of Former Rabbi Marc Gafni Tells Her Story|date=2018-01-19|url=https://www.drphil.com/videos/alleged-victim-of-former-rabbi-marc-gafni-tells-her-story/|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, an unnamed woman wrote that she was married to Gafni from 1999 to 2004 in an [[opinion piece]] in ''[[The Times of Israel]]''. The article was in response to a ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' article about Gafni the preceding week.<ref name=\"Oppenheimer2015\" /> She catalogued what she described as her story of abuse and wrote that she had gone public to \"Protect some girl. Protect some woman. Some student. Some unsuspecting soul.\"<ref name=\"ToIVoice\">{{cite news|url=http://blogs.timesofisrael.com/from-one-gafni-victim/|title=A voice for Gafni's victims, from one who was there|last=|first=|date=January 1, 2016|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|accessdate=January 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWithin two weeks of the publication of the piece in the ''[[The Times of Israel]]'', Sara Kabakov revealed in ''[[The Forward]]'' that she was the other formerly unnamed teenage girl who had been abused by Gafni in the early 1980s, beginning when she was thirteen years old.<ref name=\"Kabakov\">{{cite magazine|last=Kabakov|first=Sara|date=January 12, 2016|title='I Was 13 When Marc Gafni's Abuse Began'|url=http://forward.com/opinion/329620/i-was-13-when-marc-gafnis-abuse-began|magazine=[[The Forward]]|location=[[New York City]]|access-date=December 21, 2016}}</ref> Gafni commented, \"she was 14 going on 35, and I never forced her.\"<ref name=\"Friedman2015\" />  In a subsequent article, ''The Forward'' published Gafni's response together with the analysis of sexual abuse experts.<ref name=\"forward2\" /> Gafni included polygraph results to support his claim that his relationship with Kabakov was consensual.<ref name=\"GafniPoly\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marcgafni.com/resp/report-of-polygraph-results-october-2007/|title=Report of Polygraph Results October 2007|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|year=2015|access-date=December 28, 2016}}\n</ref><ref name=\"Barland2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marcgafni.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/02/Gafni-report-2-final-Barland.pdf|title=Report of Polygraph Examination: Marc Gafni|last=Barland|first=Gordon H.|date=December 14, 2007|website=MarcGafni.com|format=PDF|access-date=December 28, 2016|quote=\u2026this was a poor issue for the polygraph. The polygraph is believed to be most accurate when a person denies committing a specific physical act.\u2026It would be more appropriate to examine Sarah as to whether she had written a letter, than him as to whether he had read it. More importantly, testing on the contents of a letter received nearly 30 years ago is inappropriate because memory is easily modified over time \u2013 often significantly \u2013 based on additional knowledge and experience.\u2026We agreed that if he wished to be tested on this issue, I would have to include a caveat to the effect that because of the complexity of the issue, one could not have as much confidence in the results.\u2026'''Conclusion''' It is my professional opinion that Mr. Gafni answered the relevant questions truthfully. Because of the nearly three decades that have elapsed since Ms. Kabakow's letter would have been received, confidence in this conclusion is necessarily somewhat less than would otherwise be the case.}}\n</ref> Afterwards, Kabakov responded to Gafni's comments and reiterated her claim that the relationship was not consensual.<ref name=\"Kabakov2\">{{cite magazine|last=Kabakov|first=Sara|date=November 14, 2016|title=Marc Gafni Told His Side of the Story. Now His Accuser Responds.|url=http://forward.com/opinion/354282/marc-gafni-told-his-side-of-the-story-now-his-accuser-responds/|magazine=[[The Forward]]|location=[[New York City]]|access-date=April 20, 2017}}\n</ref> In February 2017, the [[National Coalition for Men]] published an article by Gafni in which he defended himself, calling the allegations \"a long-standing smear campaign\".<ref name=\"NCFM\">{{cite web|url=http://ncfm.org/2017/02/news/uncategorized/ncfm-member-marc-gafni-fake-facts-unchecked-falsehoods-that-destroy-lives/|title=NCFM Member Marc Gafni, Fake Facts: Unchecked Falsehoods that Destroy Lives|last=Gafni|first=Marc|date=February 10, 2017|publisher=[[National Coalition for Men]]|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref> This accusation was also addressed on the Dr. Phil episode of January 19, 2018.<ref name=\"Pink\" />\n\nIn 2006, after he moved to Israel, Gafni was accused by five women who attended the {{transl|he|ISO|''Bayit Hadash''}} ({{lang-he|\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea \u05d7\u05d3\u05e9|lit=new home}}) spiritual center in [[Jaffa]], which Gafni opened in the late 1990s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/news/965/rabbi-fired-over-sex-claims-defenders-offer-mea-c/|title=Rabbi Fired Over Sex Claims, Defenders Offer Mea Culpa|last=SiegelMay 19|first=Jennifer|last2=2006|website=The Forward|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> Gafni acknowledged relationships with some of the women.<ref name=\"NYP\" /> However, he characterized the relationships as consensual and supported his claim by posting [[polygraph]] results on his website.<ref name=\"Barland1b\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marcgafni.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/02/Gafni-report-1b-final-Barland.pdf|title=Report of Polygraph Examination: Marc Gafni|last=Barland|first=Gordon H.|date=October 30, 2007|website=MarcGafni.com|format=PDF|access-date=December 28, 2016|quote=In my opinion Mr. Gafni answered the relevant questions truthfully. This opinion is tempered by the fact that I had no access to the original complaints.}}\n</ref> Because of the allegations, and because Gafni fled the country to avoid prosecution,<ref name=\"Ynet-Raved\" /><ref name=\"haaretz\" /> he was dismissed from {{transl|he|ISO|''Bayit Hadash''}},<ref name=\"Heruti\">{{cite news|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/new-age-rabbi-mordechi-gafni-accused-of-sex-crimes-1.188097|title=New-age Rabbi Mordechi Gafni accused of sex crimes|last=Singer-Heruti|first=Roni|date=May 19, 2006|newspaper=[[Haaretz]]|accessdate=March 20, 2013}}\n</ref> which closed within days.<ref name=\"Shma\">{{cite journal|last=Ner-David|first=Jacob|date=December 1, 2006|title=Genug: Time for a Change|url=http://www.shma.com/dec_06/genug.htm|journal=Sh'ma: A Journal of Jewish Responsibility|location=[[Boston]]|publisher=Sh'ma Institute|archiveurl=http://www.shma.com/2006/12/genug-time-for-a-change/|archivedate=October 8, 2008|accessdate=December 28, 2016}}\n</ref> Back in the United States, Gafni sent a remorseful letter to his congregation saying he regretted his actions and... \"Clearly all of this and more indicates that in these regards I am sick. I need to acknowledge that sickness and to get help for it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewschool.com/2006/05/10587/gafnis-letter-to-aleph/|title=Gafni's Letter to Aleph \u00b7 Jewschool|date=2006-05-15|website=Jewschool|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref><ref name=\"Heruti\" /><ref name=\"Siegal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.forward.com/articles/965/|title=Rabbi Fired Over Sex Claims, Defenders Offer Mea Culpa|last=Siegal|first=Jennifer|date=May 19, 2006|publisher=[[The Forward]]|accessdate=2008-01-13}}\n</ref> Gafni later claimed the letter was not an admission of guilt but an attempt to cool the controversy.<ref name=\"gafniletter\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marcgafni.com/englishenglishhebrewhebrew-430/|title=Why I Signed the Letter|last=Gafni|first=Marc|date=May 27, 2008|accessdate=March 11, 2013}}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nGafni was the subject of new allegations of sexual misconduct in 2011.<ref name=\"JW 09132011\" /> As a result, Integral Life, one of Gafni's promoters, deleted his contributions from its website and announced that it was distancing itself from him.<ref name=\"JW 09132011\" /> Tami Simon, CEO of [[Sounds True]], canceled her planned publication of Gafni's book, ''Your Unique Self'', and issued a statement denouncing him.<ref name=\"JW 09142011\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/blogs/gary-rosenblatt/marc-gafni-again|title=Marc Gafni, Again|last1=Rosenblatt|first1=Gary|authorlink1=Gary Rosenblatt|date=September 14, 2011|newspaper=[[The Jewish Week]]|accessdate=February 27, 2013}}\n</ref> The board of directors of the Center for World Spirituality, an organization co-founded by Gafni and of which he is CEO, issued a statement of \"unequivocal support\" for Gafni.<ref name=\"support\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ievolve.org/a-cws-board-statement-of-unequivocal-support-for-dr-marc-gafni/|title=A CWS Board Statement of Unequivocal Support for Dr. Marc Gafni|date=September 2011|website=ievolve.org|publisher=Center for Integral Wisdom|access-date=December 28, 2016}}\n</ref> Wilber first separated from Gafni,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://integrallife.com/member/ken-wilber/blog/ken-wilbers-response-marc-gafni-debacle?|title=Ken Wilber's Response to the Marc Gafni Debacle|last=Wilber|first=Ken|date=October 17, 2011|publisher=Ken Wilber|access-date=March 28, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130709005615/http://integrallife.com/member/ken-wilber/blog/ken-wilbers-response-marc-gafni-debacle|archive-date=July 9, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> but the two eventually reconciled and Wilber rejoined Gafni at the Center for World Spirituality.<ref name=\"wilber11\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kenwilber.com/blog/show/701|title=Ken Wilber Statement on Marc Gafni and the Center for World Spirituality|last=Wilber|first=Ken|date=December 27, 2011|publisher=Ken Wilber}}</ref> ''Your Unique Self'' was ultimately published by Integral Publishers.<ref name=\"integralbook\">{{cite web|url=http://integralpublishers.com/ip_books/your-unique-self|title=Your Unique Self|publisher=Integral Publishers}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of these allegations, a number of new-age spiritual leaders, who had previously worked with and endorsed Gafni, have publicly withdrawn their support and written a public statement disavowing themselves from him, including [[Deepak Chopra]], Joan Borysenko, [[Andrew Harvey (religious writer)|Andrew Harvey]], author [[Jean Houston]], and Stephen Dinan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/gafni-faces-fallout-from-new-age-community/|title=Gafni Faces Fallout From New Age Community|last=Rosenblatt|first=Gary|website=jewishweek.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> Additionally, [[Zalman Schachter-Shalomi|Reb Zalman Schachter-Shalomi]], revoked his rabbinical ordination of Gafni, stating, \"It goes without saying that I withdraw my support of the Smikhah he obtained from me by deceiving me concerning his past unethical behavior. It is null and void.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/us-jewish-group-spurns-ex-rabbi-over-his-sexual-behavior/|title=US Jewish group spurns ex-rabbi over his sexual behavior|last=JTA|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewschool.com/2006/05/10681/reb-zalman-speaks-on-gafni/|title=Reb Zalman Speaks on Gafni \u00b7 Jewschool|date=2006-05-26|website=Jewschool|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*1999 ''A Certain Spirit {Vadai}: Re-Defining Certainty''\n*1999 ''Uncertainty {Safek}: Reclaiming the Spirituality of Uncertainty''\n*2002 ''Soul Prints: Your Path to Fulfillment'' {{ISBN|978-0743417006}}\n*2002 ''Seelenmuster'' {{ISBN|978-3442216062}}\n*2003 ''The Mystery of Love'' {{ISBN|978-0743442206}}\n*2005 ''Who is Afraid of Lilith? Rereading the Kabbalah of the Feminine Shadow''\n*2006 ''The Erotic and the Holy'' {{ISBN|978-1591792895}}\n*2012 ''Your Unique Self: The Radical Path to Personal Enlightenment'' {{ISBN|978-1467522779}}\n*2012 ''Radical Kabbalah'' {{ISBN|978-1467522748}}\n*2014  ''Loving Your Way to Enlightenment'' {{ISBN|978-1502305145}}\n*2014 ''Tears: Reclaiming Ritual, Integral Religion, and Rosh Hashanah'' {{ISBN|978-0989682749}}\n*2014 ''Self in Integral Evolutionary Mysticism'' {{ISBN|978-0989682787}}\n*2014 ''Your Unique Self: An Integral Path to Success 3.0'' {{ISBN|978-0990441939}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Commons category|Marc Gafni}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gafni, Marc}}\n<!-- Categories -->\n[[Category:20th-century rabbis]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:Children of Holocaust survivors]]\n[[Category:New Age writers]]\n[[Category:American spiritual writers]]\n[[Category:Integral theory]]\n[[Category:American self-help writers]]\n[[Category:Child sexual abuse in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name          = Marc Gafni\n|image         = MarcGafni.jpg\n|image_size    = \n|caption       = Marc Gafni in Rome\n|birth_name    = Marc Winiarz\n|birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1960}}\n|birth_place   = [[Pittsfield, Massachusetts]]\n|nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n|other_names   = Mordechai Gafni, Mark Gafni, Mordechai Winiarz, Mordechai Winyarz\n|education     = [[Queens College]], [[Oxford University]]\n}}\n'''Marc Gafni''' (born Marc Winiarz) is an American author and former rabbi who became a New Age spiritual teacher.<ref name=\"Rosenblatt04\"><!-- Archived article has new title of \"A Rabbi Accused of Sexual Abuse Seeks to Reinvent Himself\" but is the same as the original \"The Re-Invented Rabbi\" -->{{cite web|url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/top/editcolcontent.php3|title=The Re-Invented Rabbi|last=Rosenblatt|first=Gary|authorlink=Gary Rosenblatt|date=September 24, 2004|work=Between the Lines|publisher=[[The Jewish Week]]|archiveurl=http://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/a-rabbi-accused-of-sexual-abuse-seeks-to-reinvent-himself/|archivedate=September 30, 2004|accessdate=January 11, 2008}}</ref> One of his rabbinical ordinations was voluntarily returned and another revoked for sexual misconduct.<ref name=\"catalyst\">{{cite journal\n | last = Bell\n | first = Jeff\n |author2=Greta Belanger deJong\n |date=July 2008\n | title = Trial by Internet: An archetypal spiritual drama\n | journal = Catalyst Magazine\n | volume = 27\n | issue = 7\n | pages = 20\u201325\n | publisher = Catalyst Magazine\n | location = [[Salt Lake City]], [[Utah]]\n | url = http://www.catalystmagazine.net/pdfs/0708/catalyst_0708.pdf\n | archiveurl = http://www.catalystmagazine.net/trial-by-internet-an-archetypal-spiritual-drama/\n | archivedate = October 5, 2011\n | accessdate = December 29, 2016\n}}\n</ref><ref name = \"POJ-RR\" /><ref name = \"TantricGuru\">{{cite magazine\n| last       = Kestenbaum\n| first      = Sam\n| date       = August 2, 2016\n| title      = Former Rabbi, Accused Molester Marc Gafni Teaching at Tantric Sex School\n| url        = http://forward.com/news/346632/controverisal-new-age-guru-marc-gafnis-latest-venture-teacher-in-residence/\n| magazine   = [[The Forward]]\n| location   = New York\n| access-date= April 20, 2017\n}}\n</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewschool.com/2006/05/10681/reb-zalman-speaks-on-gafni/|title=Reb Zalman Speaks on Gafni \u00b7 Jewschool|date=2006-05-26|website=Jewschool|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> Accused of sexual assault by multiple women, Gafni acknowledged a nine-month \"relationship\" with a 14-year-old girl when he was 19;<ref name=\"Rosenblatt04\" /><ref name = \"Oppenheimer2015\">{{cite news\n| last         = Oppenheimer\n| first        = Marc\n| date         = December 25, 2015\n| title        = A Spiritual Leader Gains Stature, Trailed by a Troubled Past\n| url          = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/26/us/marc-gafni-center-for-integral-wisdom.html?smid=tw-share\n| newspaper    = [[The New York Times]]\n| access-date  = December 29, 2015\n}}\n</ref><ref name = Friedman2015>{{cite news\n| last         = Friedman\n| first        = Gabe\n| date         = December 29, 2015\n| title        = 4 quotes by ex-Orthodox rabbi Marc Gafni not in The NY Times article\n| url          = http://www.jta.org/2015/12/29/news-opinion/the-telegraph/4-quotes-by-ex-orthodox-rabbi-marc-gafni-that-the-ny-times-didnt-include\n| newspaper    = [[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]\n| access-date  = January 3, 2016\n}}\n</ref> he denies the \"relationship\" was abusive, describing it as consensual.<ref name = forward2>{{cite magazine\n| last       = Gafni\n| first      = Marc\n| date       = November 3, 2016\n| title      = Marc Gafni Tells His Story \u2014 and Experts Respond\n| url        = http://forward.com/opinion/353202/marc-gafni-tells-his-story-and-experts-respond/\n| magazine   = [[The Forward]]\n| location   = New York\n| access-date= December 15, 2016\n}}\n</ref><ref name = \"DN_McShane\">{{cite news\n| last1                 = McShane\n| first1                = Larry\n| date                  = January 2, 2016\n| title                 = New Age guru Marc Gafni allegedly molested two NYC teen girls during the 1980s, denies sexual misconduct allegations\n| url                   = http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/marc-gafni-denies-sexual-misconduct-allegations-article-1.2483567\n| newspaper             = [[New York Daily News]]\n| access-date           = December 29, 2016\n}}\n</ref><ref name = \"jewishforward\">{{cite news\n| last1                 = Ledger\n| first1                = Online\n| date                  = November 9, 2016\n| title                 = Marc Gafni: I never molested 13-year-old girl\n\n| url                   = http://www.jewishledger.com/2016/11/marc-gafni-never-molested-13-year-old-girl/\n| newspaper             = Jewish Ledger\n| access-date           = March 26, 2017\n}}\n</ref> The alleged victim states that she was 13. In 2019, Gafni was named in a sexual abuse lawsuit against Yeshiva University.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://forward.com/fast-forward/430202/marc-gafni-sexual-abuse-lawsuit-yeshiva-university/|title=Marc Gafni Named In Latest Sexual Abuse Lawsuit Against Yeshiva University|last=Feldman|first=Ari|date=|work=Forward|access-date=2019-12-28|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iapps.courts.state.ny.us/nyscef/ViewDocument?docIndex=8NgEt9dgNg9jl8rRf1DM1g==|title=Jane Doe v Yeshiva University and Marc Gafni, previously known as Mordechai Winiarz; Plantiff Affadavit|last=|first=|date=2019-08-14|website=Supreme Court of the State of New York|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nGafni was born in 1960<ref name = \"Oppenheimer2015\" /> to [[Holocaust survivors]] in [[Pittsfield, Massachusetts]].<ref name = \"POJ-RR\">{{citation |url= http://www.haaretz.com/post-orthodoxy-journey-1.115864 |title= Post-Orthodoxy Journey |last= Livneh |first= Neri |date= March 4, 2004 |newspaper= [[Haaretz]]}}</ref> Gafni was educated at Modern-Orthodox [[yeshiva]]s in the [[New York City]] area. In the 1980s, while attending [[Yeshiva University]],<ref name = \"POJ-RR\" /> Gafni worked with Jewish Public School Youth, an organization providing Jewish social clubs in public schools.<ref name=\"NYP\">{{cite news\n|url= http://www.nypost.com/news/regionalnews/66361.htm\n|title= Fiend Rabbi On Run\n|accessdate= December 28, 2016\n|last= Montefinise\n|first= Angela\n|date= May 21, 2006\n|newspaper= [[New York Post]]\n|pages = 25\n|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060614154413/http://www.nypost.com/news/regionalnews/66361.htm\n|archivedate= 2006-06-14\n}}\n</ref> In 1988, Gafni also worked as a rabbi in [[Boca Raton]], [[Florida]].<ref name=\"Rosenblatt04\" /> After making [[aliyah]], Gafni served as rabbi of the [[West Bank]] settlement of [[Tzofim]].<ref name = \"Ynet-Raved\">{{cite news\n| last1                 = Raved\n| first1                = Ahiya\n| last2                 = Cohen\n| first2                = Avi\n| date                  = May 18, 2006\n| title                 = Rabbi Gafni accused of sexual assault\n| url                   = http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3252577,00.html\n| department            = News\n| website               = [[Ynetnews]]\n| access-date           = December 28, 2016\n}}\n</ref> When Gafni moved to Israel he hebraicized his name. \"Winiarz,\" Polish for \"vintner,\" is related to the [[Hebrew]] word {{transl|he|ISO|''gefen''}} ({{rtl-lang|he|\u05d2\u05e4\u05df}}), which means \"grape\"\u2014thus the name \"Gafni.\" Gafni has three children from previous marriages<ref name = \"POJ-RR\" /> and one child with Mariana Caplan.<ref name = \"Caplan\">{{cite web\n| title       = About the Founders\n| url         = http://centerforintegralwisdom.org/ciw-founders/\n| publisher   = Center for Integral Wisdom\n| year        = 2015\n| accessdate  = December 29, 2015\n}}\n</ref><ref name = \"CIWS Bio\">{{cite web\n |url        = http://www.ievolve.org/leadership/executive-officers/#Marc_Gafni_DPhil\n |title      = Marc Gafni, D.Phil.\n |year       = 2013\n |work       = Executive Officers\n |publisher  = Center for World Spirituality\n |accessdate = February 27, 2013\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Education===\nGafni majored in philosophy as an undergraduate at Queens College, and earned his doctorate in philosophy from [[Oxford University]].<ref name = \"POJ-RR\" /><ref name = psychologytoday>{{cite magazine\n | url = https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/ethical-wisdom/201509/evolutionary-love-interview-dr-marc-gafni\n | title = Evolutionary Love: An Interview With Dr. Marc Gafni\n | last = Matousek\n | first = Mark\n | date = September 8, 2015\n | magazine = Psychology Today\n | access-date = December 29, 2016\n}}\n</ref> He returned one rabbinical ordination ''[[semikhah|(semikhah]])'' to \"spare his former teacher\" (Rabbi [[Shlomo Riskin ]]) \"any further embarrassment\".<ref name=\"Rosenblatt04\"/> His other rabbinical ordination by [[Zalman Schachter-Shalomi|Reb Zalman Schachter-Shalomi]] was revoked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewschool.com/2006/05/10681/reb-zalman-speaks-on-gafni/|title=Reb Zalman Speaks on Gafni \u00b7 Jewschool|date=2006-05-26|website=Jewschool|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/us-jewish-group-spurns-ex-rabbi-over-his-sexual-behavior/|title=US Jewish group spurns ex-rabbi over his sexual behavior|last=JTA|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n\n== Teachings ==\nGafni's teachings are described as [[Integral theory (Ken Wilber)|integral]] or world [[spirituality]], incorporating traditional religious studies with contemporary themes, and are aimed at spirituality for people who do not identify with one specific religion.<ref name = \"POJ-RR\"/><ref name=haaretz>{{cite news|last=Ganihar|first=Tomer|title=Death of the spirit|url=http://www.haaretz.com/weekend/week-s-end/death-of-the-spirit-1.366510|newspaper=Haaretz|date=June 7, 2011}}</ref> Gafni describes himself and his students as \"dual citizens\" of both their native traditional religion and the broader themes of \"world spirituality\".<ref name = \"POJ-RR\"/><ref name=dual>{{cite web|title=A Passport for Dual Citizenship with Michael Murphy & Marc Gafni|url=http://www.ievolve.org/tag/dual-citizenship/|publisher=Center for World Spirituality|date=August 8, 2011|access-date=March 3, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602103525/http://www.ievolve.org/tag/dual-citizenship/|archive-date=June 2, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> He advocates a new set of teachings around [[Eros (concept)|eros]], [[Human sexuality|sexuality]] and [[Intimate relationship|relationships]] in his book ''Mystery of Love'' and CD set ''Erotic and the Holy''.<ref name=jweek>{{cite news|last=Wall|first=Alexandra|title=Let love, sex and holiness make your life full, says rabbi|url=http://www.jweekly.com/article/full/19850/let-love-sex-and-holiness-make-your-life-full-says-rabbi/|newspaper=J Weekly|date=May 9, 2003}}</ref><ref name = \"Rosnblum2006\">{{cite news\n| url         = http://www.jpost.com/Opinion/Columnists/Think-Again-Sexualizing-the-public-square\n| title       = Think Again: 'Sexualizing' the public square \n| accessdate  = December 28, 2016\n| last        = Rosenblum\n| first       = Jonathan\n| authorlink  = Jonathan Rosenblum\n| date        = July 13, 2006\n| newspaper   = [[The Jerusalem Post]]\n}} See also Gafni, ''The Erotic And The Holy: Kabbalistic Tantra for Everyday Living''</ref> At the core of his message is what Gafni refers to as the unique self.<ref name  = \"GafniAbsract\">{{cite web\n | url = http://uniqueself.com/unique-self-theory/unique-self-basics/marc-gafni-on-unique-self/the-evolutionary-emergent-of-unique-self/\n | title = The Evolutionary Emergent of Unique Self (Abstract)\n | last = Gafni\n | first = Marc\n | year = 2011\n | website = Unique Self\n | access-date = December 20, 2016\n}}\n</ref> Gafni believes that \"the sexual is the ultimate Spiritual Master\" and has written \"I was convinced from an early age that religion had lost what I believed must have been its original erotic vitality\u2026I knew that the sexual, if liberated and ethically expressed, must somehow hold the mystery of return to the much larger-than-sexual Eros.\"<ref name = \"TantricGuru\" />\n\nIn 2010, Gafni, Mariana Caplan\u2014the mother of his son,<ref name = \"Caplan\"/> Sally Kempton, and Lori Galperin, founded the Center for World Spirituality.<ref name = \"CSWFounding\">{{cite web\n | url = http://centerforintegralwisdom.org/ciw-founders/\n | title = Founders\n | author = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->\n | year = 2015\n | website = Center for Integral Wisdom\n | access-date = December 19, 2016\n}}\n</ref> At the Center, Gafni and [[Ken Wilber]] founded a Wisdom Council to envision a spirituality based on Integral Principles.<ref name = \"CaplanCommonGround\">{{cite magazine\n| last       = Caplan\n| first      = Mariana\n| year       = 2011\n| issue      = December 2010/January 2011\n| title      = Los Angeles Makes Movies. San Francisco Makes Movements.\n| url        = http://onlinedigitaleditions2.com/commonground/archive/web-12-2010/\n| magazine   = Common Ground Magazine\n| pages      = 64\u201365\n| location   = [[Mill Valley, California]]\n| publisher  = Rob Sidon\n| access-date= December 19, 2016\n}}\n</ref> The Wisdom Council includes members such as Gafni, Wilber, [[Tony Robbins]], [[Warren Farrell]], Lori Galperin, Sally Kempton.<ref name=wisdomcouncil>{{cite web|title=Wisdom Council|url=http://www.ievolve.org/leadership/world-spirituality-council/|publisher=iEvolve|access-date=2013-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307165015/http://www.ievolve.org/leadership/world-spirituality-council/|archive-date=2013-03-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> The co-chair of Center for World Spirituality was [[Whole Foods]] [[CEO]] [[John Mackey (businessman)|John Mackey]].<ref name=mac>{{cite web|title=What is a purpose-driven business?: John Mackey and Marc Gafni in Dialogue, Part 2|url=http://www.ievolve.org/world-spirituality-unplugged-what-is-a-purpose-driven-business-john-mackey-and-marc-gafni-in-dialogue-part-1%E2%80%B3/|publisher=iEvolve|date=October 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\nGafni was a Scholar in Residence at the Integral Institute and the Director of the Integral Spiritual Experience but was asked to leave after the 2011 allegations of his sexual misconduct.<ref name = \"JW 09132011\">{{cite news\n |url          = http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/brief/new_sexual_complaints_against_marc_gafni\n |title        = New Sexual Complaints Against Marc Gafni\n |last1        = Rosenblatt\n |first1       = Gary\n |authorlink1  = Gary Rosenblatt\n |date         = September 13, 2011\n |newspaper    = [[The Jewish Week]]\n |accessdate   = December 28, 2016\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Writing===\nGafni is the author of eight books on spirituality and religion, including the 2001 ''Soul Prints''.<ref name=\"catalyst\"/> Marc Gafni's second English-language book, ''The Mystery of Love'', was later converted to an audio lecture series called ''The Erotic and the Holy'', published by [[Sounds True]]. He also co-authored ''Who is Afraid of Lilith? Rereading the Kabbalah of the Feminine Shadow'' with Ohad Ezrachi.<ref name = \"FreeLibraryLilith\">{{cite web\n | url = https://www.thefreelibrary.com/When+the+Rabbi+Met+Lilith.-a0133901938\n | title = When the Rabbi Met Lilith.\n | author = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->\n | date = July 11, 2005\n | website =  The Free Library\n | publisher = [[PR Newswire]]\n | access-date = December 21, 2016\n}}\n</ref> He wrote ''Radical Kabbalah'', a two-volume work published by Integral Publishers in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Integral Publishers|url=http://integralpublishers.com/ip_books/}}</ref> In 2012, he published ''Your Unique Self: The Radical Path to Personal Enlightenment'' with a foreword written by Wilber.<ref name = \"YUS_Forward\">{{cite web| url = http://uniqueself.com/about-the-book/take-a-look/| title = Take a Look at the Table of Contents| year = 2016| website = Unique Self| publisher = Center for Integral Wisdom| access-date = January 4, 2016}}</ref> It won a 2012 USA Best Book Awards in Spirituality: General category.<ref name = \"USABook2012\">{{cite web\n | url = http://www.usabooknews.com/images/2012_results.pdf\n | title = 2012 Reseults\n | author = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> \n | website = [[USA Book News]]\n | access-date = December 19, 2016\n | format = PDF \n | quote = }}\n</ref>\n\n===Television===\nWhile in Israel, Gafni hosted {{transl|he|ISO|''Tahat Gafno''}} ({{lang-he|\u05ea\u05d7\u05ea \u05d2\u05e4\u05e0\u05d5|lit=under his vine}}), a television program broadcast on Israel's [[Channel 2 (Israel)|Channel 2]].<ref name = \"POJ-RR\"/> Gafni also did a series of weekly television spots with Israeli comedian Gil Kopatch on biblical wisdom for every day life.<ref name = \"Kopatch2005\">{{cite news\n| last         = Kopatch\n| first        = Gil\n| date         = June 2, 2005\n| title        = Why Am I Not a Buddhist? \n| url          = http://www.haaretz.com/why-am-i-not-a-buddhist-1.160186\n| newspaper    = [[Haaretz]]\n| access-date  = December 28, 2016\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Sexual assault allegations==\nGafni has been accused of sexual assault multiple times dating back to the 1980s.<ref name=\"Rosenblatt04\"/><ref name = \"Oppenheimer2015\" /><ref name=\"NYP\" /><ref name = \"JW 09132011\" />\n\nIn early January 2016, Judy Mitzner alleged that she was one of two teenage girls whom Gafni molested in New York City in 1986.<ref name = \"Prince\">{{cite news |last=Prince |first=Cathryn J. |date=January 6, 2016 |title=Controversial ex-rabbi Gafni and an alleged victim square off |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/controversial-ex-rabbi-gafni-and-an-alleged-victim-square-off/ |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |access-date=February 7, 2018}}</ref> She reiterated those claims on an appearance on the [[Dr. Phil (talk show)|Dr. Phil]] show of January 19, 2018, in which Gafni also appeared.<ref name = \"Pink\">{{cite magazine|last=Pink|first=Aiden|date=January 21, 2018|title=Accused Child Molester Marc Gafni Defends Himself On 'Dr. Phil'|url=https://forward.com/fast-forward/392482/accused-child-molester-marc-gafni-defends-himself-on-dr-phil/|magazine=[[The Forward]]|location=[[New York City]]|access-date=February 7, 2018}}</ref> Mitzner was 16 and Gafni was 24 and he was her Jewish Youth Leader at the time.<ref>{{Citation|title=Alleged Victim Of Former Rabbi Marc Gafni Tells Her Story|date=2018-01-19|url=https://www.drphil.com/videos/alleged-victim-of-former-rabbi-marc-gafni-tells-her-story/|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, an unnamed woman wrote that she was married to Gafni from 1999 to 2004 in an [[opinion piece]] in ''[[The Times of Israel]]''. The article was in response to a ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' article about Gafni the preceding week.<ref name=\"Oppenheimer2015\" /> She catalogued what she described as her story of abuse and wrote that she had gone public to \"Protect some girl. Protect some woman. Some student. Some unsuspecting soul.\"<ref name=\"ToIVoice\">{{cite news|url=http://blogs.timesofisrael.com/from-one-gafni-victim/|title=A voice for Gafni's victims, from one who was there|last=|first=|date=January 1, 2016|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|accessdate=January 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWithin two weeks of the publication of the piece in the ''[[The Times of Israel]]'', Sara Kabakov revealed in ''[[The Forward]]'' that she was the other formerly unnamed teenage girl who had been abused by Gafni in the early 1980s, beginning when she was thirteen years old.<ref name=\"Kabakov\">{{cite magazine|last=Kabakov|first=Sara|date=January 12, 2016|title='I Was 13 When Marc Gafni's Abuse Began'|url=http://forward.com/opinion/329620/i-was-13-when-marc-gafnis-abuse-began|magazine=[[The Forward]]|location=[[New York City]]|access-date=December 21, 2016}}</ref> Gafni commented, \"she was 14 going on 35, and I never forced her.\"<ref name=\"Friedman2015\" />  In a subsequent article, ''The Forward'' published Gafni's response together with the analysis of sexual abuse experts.<ref name=\"forward2\" /> Gafni included polygraph results to support his claim that his relationship with Kabakov was consensual.<ref name=\"GafniPoly\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marcgafni.com/resp/report-of-polygraph-results-october-2007/|title=Report of Polygraph Results October 2007|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|year=2015|access-date=December 28, 2016}}\n</ref><ref name=\"Barland2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marcgafni.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/02/Gafni-report-2-final-Barland.pdf|title=Report of Polygraph Examination: Marc Gafni|last=Barland|first=Gordon H.|date=December 14, 2007|website=MarcGafni.com|format=PDF|access-date=December 28, 2016|quote=\u2026this was a poor issue for the polygraph. The polygraph is believed to be most accurate when a person denies committing a specific physical act.\u2026It would be more appropriate to examine Sarah as to whether she had written a letter, than him as to whether he had read it. More importantly, testing on the contents of a letter received nearly 30 years ago is inappropriate because memory is easily modified over time \u2013 often significantly \u2013 based on additional knowledge and experience.\u2026We agreed that if he wished to be tested on this issue, I would have to include a caveat to the effect that because of the complexity of the issue, one could not have as much confidence in the results.\u2026'''Conclusion''' It is my professional opinion that Mr. Gafni answered the relevant questions truthfully. Because of the nearly three decades that have elapsed since Ms. Kabakow's letter would have been received, confidence in this conclusion is necessarily somewhat less than would otherwise be the case.}}\n</ref> Afterwards, Kabakov responded to Gafni's comments and reiterated her claim that the relationship was not consensual.<ref name=\"Kabakov2\">{{cite magazine|last=Kabakov|first=Sara|date=November 14, 2016|title=Marc Gafni Told His Side of the Story. Now His Accuser Responds.|url=http://forward.com/opinion/354282/marc-gafni-told-his-side-of-the-story-now-his-accuser-responds/|magazine=[[The Forward]]|location=[[New York City]]|access-date=April 20, 2017}}\n</ref> In February 2017, the [[National Coalition for Men]] published an article by Gafni in which he defended himself, calling the allegations \"a long-standing smear campaign\".<ref name=\"NCFM\">{{cite web|url=http://ncfm.org/2017/02/news/uncategorized/ncfm-member-marc-gafni-fake-facts-unchecked-falsehoods-that-destroy-lives/|title=NCFM Member Marc Gafni, Fake Facts: Unchecked Falsehoods that Destroy Lives|last=Gafni|first=Marc|date=February 10, 2017|publisher=[[National Coalition for Men]]|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref> This accusation was also addressed on the Dr. Phil episode of January 19, 2018.<ref name=\"Pink\" />\n\nIn 2006, after he moved to Israel, Gafni was accused by five women who attended the {{transl|he|ISO|''Bayit Hadash''}} ({{lang-he|\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea \u05d7\u05d3\u05e9|lit=new home}}) spiritual center in [[Jaffa]], which Gafni opened in the late 1990s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/news/965/rabbi-fired-over-sex-claims-defenders-offer-mea-c/|title=Rabbi Fired Over Sex Claims, Defenders Offer Mea Culpa|last=SiegelMay 19|first=Jennifer|last2=2006|website=The Forward|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> Gafni acknowledged relationships with some of the women.<ref name=\"NYP\" /> However, he characterized the relationships as consensual and supported his claim by posting [[polygraph]] results on his website.<ref name=\"Barland1b\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marcgafni.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/02/Gafni-report-1b-final-Barland.pdf|title=Report of Polygraph Examination: Marc Gafni|last=Barland|first=Gordon H.|date=October 30, 2007|website=MarcGafni.com|format=PDF|access-date=December 28, 2016|quote=In my opinion Mr. Gafni answered the relevant questions truthfully. This opinion is tempered by the fact that I had no access to the original complaints.}}\n</ref> Because of the allegations, and because Gafni fled the country to avoid prosecution,<ref name=\"Ynet-Raved\" /><ref name=\"haaretz\" /> he was dismissed from {{transl|he|ISO|''Bayit Hadash''}},<ref name=\"Heruti\">{{cite news|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/new-age-rabbi-mordechi-gafni-accused-of-sex-crimes-1.188097|title=New-age Rabbi Mordechi Gafni accused of sex crimes|last=Singer-Heruti|first=Roni|date=May 19, 2006|newspaper=[[Haaretz]]|accessdate=March 20, 2013}}\n</ref> which closed within days.<ref name=\"Shma\">{{cite journal|last=Ner-David|first=Jacob|date=December 1, 2006|title=Genug: Time for a Change|url=http://www.shma.com/dec_06/genug.htm|journal=Sh'ma: A Journal of Jewish Responsibility|location=[[Boston]]|publisher=Sh'ma Institute|archiveurl=http://www.shma.com/2006/12/genug-time-for-a-change/|archivedate=October 8, 2008|accessdate=December 28, 2016}}\n</ref> Back in the United States, Gafni sent a remorseful letter to his congregation saying he regretted his actions and... \"Clearly all of this and more indicates that in these regards I am sick. I need to acknowledge that sickness and to get help for it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewschool.com/2006/05/10587/gafnis-letter-to-aleph/|title=Gafni's Letter to Aleph \u00b7 Jewschool|date=2006-05-15|website=Jewschool|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref><ref name=\"Heruti\" /><ref name=\"Siegal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.forward.com/articles/965/|title=Rabbi Fired Over Sex Claims, Defenders Offer Mea Culpa|last=Siegal|first=Jennifer|date=May 19, 2006|publisher=[[The Forward]]|accessdate=2008-01-13}}\n</ref> Gafni later claimed the letter was not an admission of guilt but an attempt to cool the controversy.<ref name=\"gafniletter\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marcgafni.com/englishenglishhebrewhebrew-430/|title=Why I Signed the Letter|last=Gafni|first=Marc|date=May 27, 2008|accessdate=March 11, 2013}}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nGafni was the subject of new allegations of sexual misconduct in 2011.<ref name=\"JW 09132011\" /> As a result, Integral Life, one of Gafni's promoters, deleted his contributions from its website and announced that it was distancing itself from him.<ref name=\"JW 09132011\" /> Tami Simon, CEO of [[Sounds True]], canceled her planned publication of Gafni's book, ''Your Unique Self'', and issued a statement denouncing him.<ref name=\"JW 09142011\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/blogs/gary-rosenblatt/marc-gafni-again|title=Marc Gafni, Again|last1=Rosenblatt|first1=Gary|authorlink1=Gary Rosenblatt|date=September 14, 2011|newspaper=[[The Jewish Week]]|accessdate=February 27, 2013}}\n</ref> The board of directors of the Center for World Spirituality, an organization co-founded by Gafni and of which he is CEO, issued a statement of \"unequivocal support\" for Gafni.<ref name=\"support\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ievolve.org/a-cws-board-statement-of-unequivocal-support-for-dr-marc-gafni/|title=A CWS Board Statement of Unequivocal Support for Dr. Marc Gafni|date=September 2011|website=ievolve.org|publisher=Center for Integral Wisdom|access-date=December 28, 2016}}\n</ref> Wilber first separated from Gafni,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://integrallife.com/member/ken-wilber/blog/ken-wilbers-response-marc-gafni-debacle?|title=Ken Wilber's Response to the Marc Gafni Debacle|last=Wilber|first=Ken|date=October 17, 2011|publisher=Ken Wilber|access-date=March 28, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130709005615/http://integrallife.com/member/ken-wilber/blog/ken-wilbers-response-marc-gafni-debacle|archive-date=July 9, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> but the two eventually reconciled and Wilber rejoined Gafni at the Center for World Spirituality.<ref name=\"wilber11\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kenwilber.com/blog/show/701|title=Ken Wilber Statement on Marc Gafni and the Center for World Spirituality|last=Wilber|first=Ken|date=December 27, 2011|publisher=Ken Wilber}}</ref> ''Your Unique Self'' was ultimately published by Integral Publishers.<ref name=\"integralbook\">{{cite web|url=http://integralpublishers.com/ip_books/your-unique-self|title=Your Unique Self|publisher=Integral Publishers}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of these allegations, a number of new-age spiritual leaders, who had previously worked with and endorsed Gafni, have publicly withdrawn their support and written a public statement disavowing themselves from him, including [[Deepak Chopra]], Joan Borysenko, [[Andrew Harvey (religious writer)|Andrew Harvey]], author [[Jean Houston]], and Stephen Dinan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/gafni-faces-fallout-from-new-age-community/|title=Gafni Faces Fallout From New Age Community|last=Rosenblatt|first=Gary|website=jewishweek.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> Additionally, [[Zalman Schachter-Shalomi|Reb Zalman Schachter-Shalomi]], revoked his rabbinical ordination of Gafni, stating, \"It goes without saying that I withdraw my support of the Smikhah he obtained from me by deceiving me concerning his past unethical behavior. It is null and void.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/us-jewish-group-spurns-ex-rabbi-over-his-sexual-behavior/|title=US Jewish group spurns ex-rabbi over his sexual behavior|last=JTA|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewschool.com/2006/05/10681/reb-zalman-speaks-on-gafni/|title=Reb Zalman Speaks on Gafni \u00b7 Jewschool|date=2006-05-26|website=Jewschool|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*1999 ''A Certain Spirit {Vadai}: Re-Defining Certainty''\n*1999 ''Uncertainty {Safek}: Reclaiming the Spirituality of Uncertainty''\n*2002 ''Soul Prints: Your Path to Fulfillment'' {{ISBN|978-0743417006}}\n*2002 ''Seelenmuster'' {{ISBN|978-3442216062}}\n*2003 ''The Mystery of Love'' {{ISBN|978-0743442206}}\n*2005 ''Who is Afraid of Lilith? Rereading the Kabbalah of the Feminine Shadow''\n*2006 